'''Mary Childs Nerney''' was the Executive Secretary of the [[NAACP]] from 1912 to 1916.<ref name="Inc.1999">{{cite book|author=The Crisis Publishing Company, Inc.|title=The Crisis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S1kEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA77|date=1999|publisher=The Crisis Publishing Company, Inc.|pages=77–|issn=0011-1422}}</ref> She was white, and often lost patience with the African-American people she was seeking to help.<ref name="Jones2001">{{cite book|author=Larry Eugene Jones|title=Crossing Boundaries: The Exclusion and Inclusion of Minorities in Germany and the United States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f9ARfEA0nLoC&pg=PA198|year=2001|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=978-1-57181-306-0|pages=198–}}</ref>

She offered [[W.E.B. DuBois]] the chance to lead the campaign to ban ''[[The Birth of a Nation]]'' (1915), but he refused.<ref>{{cite book|title=Reconstruction in the Mind of W.E.B. Du Bois: Myth, Memory, and the Meaning of American Democracy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I2bq6y0534sC&pg=PA237|year=2008|publisher=ProQuest|isbn=978-0-549-77584-3|pages=237–}}</ref> Because of the lack of success in NAACP's actions to ban ''The Birth of a Nation'', on April 17, 1915, Nerney wrote to NAACP Executive Committee member George Packard: "I am utterly disgusted with the situation in regard to ''The Birth of a Nation'' ... kindly remember that we have put six weeks of constant effort of this thing and have gotten nowhere."<ref name="historymatters">{{cite web|last1=Nerney|first1=Mary Childs|title=An NAACP Official Calls for Censorship of The Birth of a Nation|url=http://historymatters.gmu.edu/d/4966/|website=History Matters|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref>

